<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06172022 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06172022 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  USSR; WEST; ECONOMY; AGREEMENT; DELAY; GOVERNMENT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Soviet Union is not yet ready to enter a &quot;grand bargain&quot; with Westernnations, under which the West would give massive aid to help convert theSoviet economy into a modern market system.;    On that essential point, boththe Harvard University authors of the much-discussed aid proposal and severalof their most prominent critics agreed Wednesday, in testimony before a SenateForeign Relations subcommittee.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  EXPERTS: SOVIETS NOT READY FOR A 'GRAND BARGAIN'  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See also related story on page 1A andamp; 12A in this section  </MEMO><TEXT>     Even Jeffrey Sachs, the Harvard economist most closely identified with theproposed &quot;grand bargain,&quot; stated frankly that: &quot;I would say stay out of it sofar, they're not there yet.&quot;;    Sachs and Soviet economist Grigory Yavlinskydrafted the aid plan as a guide to Soviet and Western policy-makers on howthey might work together to transform the collapsing Soviet economy into aWestern-style market system.;    While no government endorses the programfully, it clearly is influencing debate throughout world capitals as SovietPresident Mikhail Gorbachev prepares to meet Western leaders at a Londoneconomic summit July 15-17.;    Western aid must be given only in step-by-stepdoses as the Soviets achieve specific reforms, Sachs said. But in a recentspeech in Oslo, Norway, Gorbachev said such conditions would be unacceptableintrusions on Soviet sovereignty.;    &quot;I can understand that, but it doesn'tmean I have to give them money,&quot; said Marshall I. Goldman, associate directorof Harvard's Russian Research Center and a prominent skeptic about the &quot;grandbargain.&quot;;    Regarding that plan, Goldman said: &quot;There's almost a feelingthat if you throw enough money at the problem, the problem will be solved.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  ROBERT A. RANKIN, Mercury News Washington Bureau  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910620  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  12A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  272  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday June 20, 199100172022,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>